PASSENGER INFORMATION
Sunworld Flies 737-300 & DC-9 Jets
SUNWORLD is not responsible for lost tickets. Please ensure that you exercise complete
and proper control of your ticket. FARES SUBJECT TO CHANGE WITHOUT NOTICE.
SCHEDULES - Schedules shown are expected departures and arrivals, as planned at the
time of publication and are subject to change without notice. Actual times should be confirmed
wnen making reservations. because weatner and otner tactors may artect sate operating con-
ditions, SUNWORLD can't guarantee its schedules or accept liability for delays in flight arrivals
or depantures, or tor missea connections. In the event or delays, we will work to minimize any
inconvenience to you. During holiday periods our schedules may be adjusted slightly. Please
check with your nearest SUNWORLD ticket or reservation office for any changes.
RESERVATIONS/TICKET PURCHASES — Advance reservations are recommended and may
be obtained for any flight by contacting SUNWORLD or your travel agent. Reservations are
subject to cancellation it tickets have not been purchased at least 60 minutes prior to departure
or prior to the time agreed upon at the time the reservations were confirmed with the airline.
It is to your advantage to purchase your tickets early. Once you have purchased your ticket
and as long as you do not change your flights or dates of travel, your fare will be guaranteed
even if the fare increases before you travel. Seats may be reserved onboard the aircraft for
travel only on the date of departure upon your presentation at the departure gate or designated
check-in location.
BAGGAGE REGULATIONS — For each ticketed passenger, the free baggage allowance is
two checked bags not over 62 inches and 55 inches respectively. In addition, carry-on bag-
gage may remain in the passenger's possession and be carried aboard SUNWORLD's aircraft
provided its dimensions allow storage beneath a passenger seat or in the overhead compart-
ments. Each additional piece checked will be subject to a service charge. SUNWORLD Air-
ways' liability for baggage claims is limited to $1,250.00 per passenger or the actual supported
value, whichever is less.
Baggage checking tips in order to serve you better:
• Please include your name, address and telephone number on both the inside and outside
of your baggage.
• Don't place jewelry, money, important medicine, one of a kind documents or fragile
items such as cameras or radios in checked baggage.
CHECK-IN TIME — All ticketed passengers not in possession of a seat selection should be
at an airport ticket lifting point to obtain their boarding pass at least 30 minutes prior to depar-
ture of their flight. Reservations may be cancelled if the passenger has not presented himself
at the loading gate at least 10 minutes prior to scheduled departure time, or it will render him
ineligible for denied boarding compensation.
RESTRICTED ARTICLES — The following articles are classified as hazardous and must not
be in baggage: compressed gases (excludina aerosol containers tor personal use). corrosives.
exprosives, Tammabies, oxiaizing materals, poisons, onercases with installed alarm devices.
radioactive and magnetic materials and all other items restricted by government regulation.
AM and FM radio receivers and TV receivers may not be operated during the flight, as they
might interfere with navigation and communications equipment.
ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES — Federal Aviation Administration regulations provide that no per-
sons may drink alcoholic beverages on board an aircraft unless they have been served by the
airline. SUNWORLD will only serve alcoholic beverages provided by our commissary for use
inflight, and no such beverage may be served to any person who appears intoxicated or under
the age of 21.
CHILDREN — One child under 2 years of age, not occupying a seat and accompanied by a
tare-paying passenger over 11 vears ot age. will be transported without charge. Children ages
2 through 11 may be eligible for various discounts, provided certain eligibility and travel re-
quirements are satisfied. Please contact SUNWORLD for further information.
NOTICE - OVERBOOKING OF FLIGHTS
Airline flights may be overbooked, and there is a slight chance that a seat will not be available
on a flight for which a person has a confirmed reservation. If the flight is overbooked, no one
will be denied a seat until airline personnel first ask for volunteers willing to give up their reser
vation in exchange for payment of the airline's choosing. If there are not enough volunteers,
the airline will deny boarding to other persons in accordance with its particular boarding prior-
ity. With a few exceptions, persons denied boarding involuntarily are entitled to compensation.
The complete rules for the payment of compensation and each airline's boarding priorities are
available at all airport ticket counters and boarding locations.
2015.126,066
